00:17:03.340 --> 00:17:04.569 align:middle line:90%
No, I don't want to do this.

00:17:04.569 --> 00:17:07.440 align:middle line:84%
We had conversations,
I would say, over

00:17:07.440 --> 00:17:08.440 align:middle line:90%
about a two week period.

00:17:08.440 --> 00:17:09.829 align:middle line:90%
It really took some convincing.

00:17:09.829 --> 00:17:13.990 align:middle line:84%
He really had to kind of
have a lot of conversations

00:17:13.990 --> 00:17:18.310 align:middle line:84%
about the pros, the cons,
what was better or not better

00:17:18.310 --> 00:17:20.109 align:middle line:90%
about me doing that.

00:17:20.109 --> 00:17:22.210 align:middle line:90%
And I was convinced over time.

00:17:22.210 --> 00:17:24.040 align:middle line:84%
But at first, no I was
incredibly reluctant

00:17:24.040 --> 00:17:26.109 align:middle line:84%
and had no interest in
doing this job whatsoever.

00:17:26.109 --> 00:17:28.734 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Well, I've got to tell
you, Randy, I have interviewed,

00:17:28.734 --> 00:17:31.690 align:middle line:84%
in my career,
thousands of people--

00:17:31.690 --> 00:17:34.190 align:middle line:90%
thousands of people.

00:17:34.190 --> 00:17:37.240 align:middle line:84%
There's an element
of belief to you.

00:17:37.240 --> 00:17:39.790 align:middle line:90%
I'm looking for body language.

00:17:39.790 --> 00:17:42.440 align:middle line:90%
I'm looking for signs.

00:17:42.440 --> 00:17:43.870 align:middle line:90%
And I don't see it from you.

00:17:43.870 --> 00:17:46.660 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: Well, when I was
first talking with my Brigadier

00:17:46.660 --> 00:17:52.489 align:middle line:84%
and we were discussing how I
should talk or how I should

00:17:52.489 --> 00:17:53.530 align:middle line:90%
present the information--

00:17:53.530 --> 00:17:55.660 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Have you been
schooled in this interview?

00:17:55.660 --> 00:17:56.767 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: No, no, no, no.

00:17:56.767 --> 00:17:58.600 align:middle line:84%
Just like I said, in
the very beginning when

00:17:58.600 --> 00:18:01.360 align:middle line:84%
my Brigadier and I were
having conversations about how

00:18:01.360 --> 00:18:03.346 align:middle line:84%
to talk to people or how
to talk to the public

00:18:03.346 --> 00:18:04.720 align:middle line:84%
and one of my
questions was, what

00:18:04.720 --> 00:18:06.370 align:middle line:90%
do you want me to tell people?

00:18:06.370 --> 00:18:08.151 align:middle line:84%
How do you want me to
package information?

00:18:08.151 --> 00:18:09.400 align:middle line:90%
How do you want me to do this?

00:18:09.400 --> 00:18:12.610 align:middle line:84%
And he basically said, it
is the most important thing

00:18:12.610 --> 00:18:14.990 align:middle line:84%
that you do nothing other
than tell the truth.

00:18:14.990 --> 00:18:17.750 align:middle line:84%
He said, don't package anything
in a way that isn't truthful,

00:18:17.750 --> 00:18:18.550 align:middle line:90%
that isn't honest.

00:18:18.550 --> 00:18:21.017 align:middle line:84%
Don't misrepresent yourself
in any way, shape, or form.

00:18:21.017 --> 00:18:23.350 align:middle line:84%
He said, the most important
thing that we want you to do

00:18:23.350 --> 00:18:27.240 align:middle line:84%
is be 100% honest, 100%
truthful all the time.

00:18:27.240 --> 00:18:29.110 align:middle line:84%
He said, now, there
may be certain things

00:18:29.110 --> 00:18:30.637 align:middle line:84%
that you don't
want to tell people

00:18:30.637 --> 00:18:32.470 align:middle line:84%
or you don't want to
share because you think

00:18:32.470 --> 00:18:34.595 align:middle line:84%
it may be a little too
outside the box and he said,

00:18:34.595 --> 00:18:35.590 align:middle line:90%
that's your call.

00:18:35.590 --> 00:18:36.330 align:middle line:90%
If you don't want to share--

00:18:36.330 --> 00:18:37.870 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: I want outside the box.

00:18:37.870 --> 00:18:39.580 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: He says, if you've
had an experience that you think

00:18:39.580 --> 00:18:41.996 align:middle line:84%
is a little too outside the
box and you don't want to talk

00:18:41.996 --> 00:18:43.415 align:middle line:90%
about it, that's up to you.

00:18:43.415 --> 00:18:45.790 align:middle line:84%
He said, I just want to make
sure that you understand you

00:18:45.790 --> 00:18:48.010 align:middle line:84%
always be honest you
always tell the truth

00:18:48.010 --> 00:18:51.580 align:middle line:84%
and you never deviate from
that as much as possible

00:18:51.580 --> 00:18:53.510 align:middle line:90%
because people can feel that.

00:18:53.510 --> 00:18:54.310 align:middle line:90%
People can hear it.

00:18:54.310 --> 00:18:55.210 align:middle line:90%
People can sense it.

00:18:55.210 --> 00:18:56.980 align:middle line:84%
And the last thing
we want is for people

00:18:56.980 --> 00:18:59.063 align:middle line:84%
to think that you're not
being honest or truthful.

00:18:59.063 --> 00:19:02.730 align:middle line:84%
So from day one, I have
endeavored to just be--

00:19:02.730 --> 00:19:04.660 align:middle line:84%
to sort of get out
of my own way as it

00:19:04.660 --> 00:19:06.250 align:middle line:84%
were when I talk to
people about this

00:19:06.250 --> 00:19:09.070 align:middle line:84%
and just tell people
the absolute truth

00:19:09.070 --> 00:19:12.380 align:middle line:84%
from the best of my recollection
of what I remember happened.

00:19:12.380 --> 00:19:16.930 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Let's talk about the
Moon trip first and then Mars.

00:19:16.930 --> 00:19:20.440 align:middle line:84%
And you can explain to us
some of the things that I'm

00:19:20.440 --> 00:19:22.330 align:middle line:90%
going to ask you in a second.

00:19:22.330 --> 00:19:25.350 align:middle line:84%
When did the Moon trip
occur, the first one for you?

00:19:25.350 --> 00:19:26.350 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: The first one?

00:19:26.350 --> 00:19:26.590 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yes.

00:19:26.590 --> 00:19:27.550 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: Oh, I
mean, the first one

00:19:27.550 --> 00:19:28.930 align:middle line:90%
would have been in childhood.

00:19:28.930 --> 00:19:30.730 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: They took you as a kid?

00:19:30.730 --> 00:19:32.680 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: Oh, we
started training

00:19:32.680 --> 00:19:34.840 align:middle line:84%
when I was probably about
four or five years old.

00:19:34.840 --> 00:19:39.790 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Well, now we landed
on the Moon, "officially" 1969.

00:19:39.790 --> 00:19:41.990 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: Unofficially,
we landed on the Moon

00:19:41.990 --> 00:19:43.450 align:middle line:90%
a couple of decades before that.

00:19:43.450 --> 00:19:45.250 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: So you think
we went to the moon

00:19:45.250 --> 00:19:48.040 align:middle line:84%
before Neil Armstrong
and Buzz Aldrin?

00:19:48.040 --> 00:19:51.520 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: The military had the
first lunar base, I believe,

00:19:51.520 --> 00:19:53.842 align:middle line:90%
built in about 1955.

00:19:53.842 --> 00:19:56.050 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Who might be the
first American on the Moon,

00:19:56.050 --> 00:19:57.640 align:middle line:90%
if it wasn't Neil Armstrong?

00:19:57.640 --> 00:20:00.910 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: Some nameless
covert military space program

00:20:00.910 --> 00:20:02.790 align:middle line:84%
astronaut who we'll
probably never know.

00:20:02.790 --> 00:20:04.540 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I certainly
don't know who it was.

00:20:04.540 --> 00:20:06.947 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Did anybody die
of tragedy on the Moon?

00:20:06.947 --> 00:20:09.280 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: I would say almost
certainly in the early days

00:20:09.280 --> 00:20:11.860 align:middle line:84%
because even though
they were using advanced

00:20:11.860 --> 00:20:14.830 align:middle line:84%
reverse engineered technology
from extraterrestrial vehicles

00:20:14.830 --> 00:20:16.660 align:middle line:84%
that we had recovered
in the '40s,

00:20:16.660 --> 00:20:17.980 align:middle line:90%
it's still the early days.

00:20:17.980 --> 00:20:20.750 align:middle line:84%
So mistakes were made
and I'm sure people died

00:20:20.750 --> 00:20:21.550 align:middle line:90%
in the process.

00:20:21.550 --> 00:20:24.856 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Did Armstrong and
Aldrin know about this program?

00:20:24.856 --> 00:20:26.230 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: There's
some discussion

00:20:26.230 --> 00:20:29.740 align:middle line:84%
about that but most people
internally agree that they

00:20:29.740 --> 00:20:31.810 align:middle line:90%
had some briefing about that.

00:20:31.810 --> 00:20:33.760 align:middle line:84%
In fact, they knew that
when they got there,

00:20:33.760 --> 00:20:37.240 align:middle line:84%
one of their main
missions was to look for

00:20:37.240 --> 00:20:42.460 align:middle line:84%
and/or explore artifacts or
a very old crashed vehicle--

00:20:42.460 --> 00:20:43.510 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Or facilities.

00:20:43.510 --> 00:20:44.615 align:middle line:90%
Did they find them?

00:20:44.615 --> 00:20:46.240 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: My
understanding is they did.

00:20:46.240 --> 00:20:48.615 align:middle line:84%
My understanding that was part
of their job and they did.

00:20:48.615 --> 00:20:50.995 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: All right, so
you go there as a kid.

00:20:50.995 --> 00:20:51.795 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: Yep.

00:20:51.795 --> 00:20:53.920 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Why take
a kid to the Moon?

00:20:53.920 --> 00:20:55.270 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: Training.

00:20:55.270 --> 00:20:59.650 align:middle line:84%
The training process from four
years old to 17 years old--

00:20:59.650 --> 00:21:00.790 align:middle line:90%
it was vast.

00:21:00.790 --> 00:21:03.200 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Are you in a
space suit over there?

00:21:03.200 --> 00:21:06.040 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: No, most of the time
it's in this base called Lunar

00:21:06.040 --> 00:21:09.520 align:middle line:84%
Operations Command, which is a
vast underground facility that

00:21:09.520 --> 00:21:12.820 align:middle line:84%
has some top ground facility
but most of it is stories

00:21:12.820 --> 00:21:13.850 align:middle line:90%
and levels and levels--

00:21:13.850 --> 00:21:15.580 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Do you
remember landing there?

00:21:15.580 --> 00:21:19.980 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: I can remember coming
in a couple of times on a TR-3B

00:21:19.980 --> 00:21:23.190 align:middle line:84%
and entering into a hangar,
coming down on an elevator

00:21:23.190 --> 00:21:23.990 align:middle line:90%
and--

00:21:23.990 --> 00:21:25.050 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: And it closes?

00:21:25.050 --> 00:21:27.670 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: And the elevator
basically comes down

00:21:27.670 --> 00:21:29.310 align:middle line:90%
onto a landing platform.

00:21:29.310 --> 00:21:31.930 align:middle line:84%
It drops, which turns out
to be a large elevator,

00:21:31.930 --> 00:21:33.100 align:middle line:90%
drops down into an elevator.

00:21:33.100 --> 00:21:35.110 align:middle line:84%
The landing platform
closes and then

00:21:35.110 --> 00:21:37.780 align:middle line:84%
it's in a large hangar,
which is like stacks

00:21:37.780 --> 00:21:38.899 align:middle line:90%
and stacks of bookshelves.

00:21:38.899 --> 00:21:39.940 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: All underground?

00:21:39.940 --> 00:21:43.240 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: Yeah, except each
bookshelf is a square unit

00:21:43.240 --> 00:21:44.400 align:middle line:90%
that a ship can park into.

00:21:44.400 --> 00:21:47.740 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And how many people
are with you on this journey?

00:21:47.740 --> 00:21:51.040 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: It would vary but
I would say on the vehicle

00:21:51.040 --> 00:21:55.130 align:middle line:84%
at any given time anywhere
from 15 to 30 other recruits

00:21:55.130 --> 00:21:55.930 align:middle line:90%
or passengers.

00:21:55.930 --> 00:21:57.522 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Primarily kids?

00:21:57.522 --> 00:21:59.230 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: Primarily
of the same age group

00:21:59.230 --> 00:22:00.530 align:middle line:90%
of whatever I was at the time.

00:22:00.530 --> 00:22:02.710 align:middle line:84%
So if I was five, it was
a bunch of five-year-olds.

00:22:02.710 --> 00:22:04.600 align:middle line:84%
If I was 10, it was a
bunch of 10-year-olds.

00:22:04.600 --> 00:22:06.550 align:middle line:84%
If I was 13, it was a
bunch of 13-year-olds.

00:22:06.550 --> 00:22:09.280 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: So at what age did
you stop going to the Moon?

00:22:09.280 --> 00:22:12.666 align:middle line:90%


00:22:12.666 --> 00:22:14.790 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: I mean, I don't
know about stopped going.

00:22:14.790 --> 00:22:19.350 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it was on and off all
the way up until my deployment

00:22:19.350 --> 00:22:21.570 align:middle line:90%
to my tour when I was 17.

00:22:21.570 --> 00:22:24.474 align:middle line:84%
And then the return trip
was a stop at the Moon and--

00:22:24.474 --> 00:22:26.390 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Then you started
going to Mars, which

00:22:26.390 --> 00:22:27.660 align:middle line:90%
we'll get into in a second.

00:22:27.660 --> 00:22:27.740 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: Right.

00:22:27.740 --> 00:22:29.490 align:middle line:84%
And then after the
tour of duty to Mars,

00:22:29.490 --> 00:22:32.910 align:middle line:84%
it was another return trip back
to Lunar Operations Command

00:22:32.910 --> 00:22:34.710 align:middle line:84%
for what they call
"age reversing."

00:22:34.710 --> 00:22:36.330 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: What are
they doing there?

00:22:36.330 --> 00:22:37.590 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: What do you mean,
what are they doing there?

00:22:37.590 --> 00:22:38.925 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Yeah, what
are they doing?

00:22:38.925 --> 00:22:40.050 align:middle line:90%
They're there for purpose.

00:22:40.050 --> 00:22:41.674 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: What aren't
they doing there?

00:22:41.674 --> 00:22:43.650 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: What's the purpose?

00:22:43.650 --> 00:22:46.140 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: To have the
largest forward operating

00:22:46.140 --> 00:22:48.930 align:middle line:84%
station for the covert
military space program that's

00:22:48.930 --> 00:22:50.970 align:middle line:90%
not based on planet Earth.

00:22:50.970 --> 00:22:52.560 align:middle line:84%
Because the most
secure place you

00:22:52.560 --> 00:22:56.130 align:middle line:84%
can have something is
where no civilian can

00:22:56.130 --> 00:22:58.590 align:middle line:84%
walk across a boundary
line or cross a fence.

00:22:58.590 --> 00:23:01.680 align:middle line:84%
And no one can walk across
from here to the Moon

00:23:01.680 --> 00:23:03.760 align:middle line:84%
or across that fence,
or across that yard so

00:23:03.760 --> 00:23:05.010 align:middle line:90%
to speak, without a spaceship.

00:23:05.010 --> 00:23:07.410 align:middle line:84%
So it's the most
secure place to have

00:23:07.410 --> 00:23:10.740 align:middle line:84%
a covert military operating
facilities on the Moon

00:23:10.740 --> 00:23:12.360 align:middle line:90%
or farther out.

00:23:12.360 --> 00:23:13.890 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Amazing.

00:23:13.890 --> 00:23:14.820 align:middle line:90%
It truly is--

00:23:14.820 --> 00:23:15.850 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: But from
what I understand,

00:23:15.850 --> 00:23:16.710 align:middle line:90%
they're doing everything there.

00:23:16.710 --> 00:23:17.790 align:middle line:90%
They do training there.

00:23:17.790 --> 00:23:19.690 align:middle line:84%
They're doing science
experiments there.

00:23:19.690 --> 00:23:23.070 align:middle line:84%
There's a certain amount
of civilian personnel

00:23:23.070 --> 00:23:25.320 align:middle line:84%
that come to visit
to observe what's

00:23:25.320 --> 00:23:27.660 align:middle line:84%
going on in the covert
military space program.

00:23:27.660 --> 00:23:30.810 align:middle line:84%
There's financiers, bankers,
who are dealing with the money

00:23:30.810 --> 00:23:31.710 align:middle line:90%
side of the program.

00:23:31.710 --> 00:23:35.250 align:middle line:84%
It's a massive, massive
military facility.

00:23:35.250 --> 00:23:37.900 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And the
facility is just huge?

00:23:37.900 --> 00:23:39.270 align:middle line:90%
How did they build it?

00:23:39.270 --> 00:23:40.965 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: Over time.

00:23:40.965 --> 00:23:43.350 align:middle line:84%
Keep digging down and
down and building large--

00:23:43.350 --> 00:23:46.680 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: So they must
have sent equipment--

00:23:46.680 --> 00:23:47.550 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: Oh yeah.

00:23:47.550 --> 00:23:49.350 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: --digging equipment.

00:23:49.350 --> 00:23:52.860 align:middle line:84%
So the size of the crafts
to get that stuff there

00:23:52.860 --> 00:23:54.660 align:middle line:90%
must have been huge.

00:23:54.660 --> 00:23:56.760 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: Some of them
were probably pretty big.

00:23:56.760 --> 00:23:59.960 align:middle line:84%
Some of the early
Aurora saucer craft

00:23:59.960 --> 00:24:01.710 align:middle line:84%
are you know the size
of a football field.

00:24:01.710 --> 00:24:05.100 align:middle line:84%
I mean, they're 100 meters,
300 feet wide or so.

00:24:05.100 --> 00:24:08.250 align:middle line:84%
So they could put a whole bunch
of a construction equipment

00:24:08.250 --> 00:24:10.400 align:middle line:90%
on a vehicle that big.

00:24:10.400 --> 00:24:15.080 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: The whistleblower,
