And you've seen the pictures
of US Navy spaceships, Solar

00:25:05.330 --> 00:25:06.830 align:middle line:10%
Warden.

00:25:06.830 --> 00:25:11.000 align:middle line:10%
So Solar Warden came out
of a think tank inside

00:25:11.000 --> 00:25:12.740 align:middle line:10%
of engineering at Douglas.

00:25:12.740 --> 00:25:18.310 align:middle line:10%
And a whole lot of
other stuff came out.

00:25:18.310 --> 00:25:19.870 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Why would he be lying?

00:25:19.870 --> 00:25:21.040 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: Oh, he's not.

00:25:21.040 --> 00:25:23.770 align:middle line:84%
I spent the end of my 20
year career as a pilot

00:25:23.770 --> 00:25:25.332 align:middle line:90%
aboard the EDF SS Nautilus.

00:25:25.332 --> 00:25:27.790 align:middle line:84%
The Nautilus is one of those
ships that's a couple of miles

00:25:27.790 --> 00:25:27.900 align:middle line:90%
long.

00:25:27.900 --> 00:25:28.721 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: One of his designs?

00:25:28.721 --> 00:25:29.780 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: Yeah, yeah.

00:25:29.780 --> 00:25:31.270 align:middle line:84%
It's basically an
aircraft carrier

00:25:31.270 --> 00:25:32.820 align:middle line:90%
that's like a long tube.

00:25:32.820 --> 00:25:33.760 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Geez.

00:25:33.760 --> 00:25:37.810 align:middle line:84%
Branding is absolutely
amazing-- the story.

00:25:37.810 --> 00:25:39.550 align:middle line:90%
So you're on the Moon.

00:25:39.550 --> 00:25:42.040 align:middle line:84%
You're doing things,
you're doing studies.

00:25:42.040 --> 00:25:47.140 align:middle line:84%
What was the time period you
would stay at any given time?

00:25:47.140 --> 00:25:50.680 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: I would say
anywhere from about 16 hours

00:25:50.680 --> 00:25:52.807 align:middle line:90%
to two or three weeks at a time.

00:25:52.807 --> 00:25:54.640 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: So nothing
really longer than that?

00:25:54.640 --> 00:25:56.723 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: No, that was
usually a training session.

00:25:56.723 --> 00:25:58.840 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Were they constantly
replacing personnel

00:25:58.840 --> 00:26:02.516 align:middle line:84%
or were people there
for three, four years?

00:26:02.516 --> 00:26:05.140 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: I don't know what the
typical tour of duty for people

00:26:05.140 --> 00:26:06.850 align:middle line:84%
at Lunar Operations
Command is but I

00:26:06.850 --> 00:26:09.370 align:middle line:84%
know there is a constant
rotation of personnel.

00:26:09.370 --> 00:26:12.760 align:middle line:84%
When I was in the MDF,
we had a weekly rotation

00:26:12.760 --> 00:26:15.730 align:middle line:84%
of we would lose
people that would die

00:26:15.730 --> 00:26:19.330 align:middle line:84%
and then we would end up having
new people come in every week.

00:26:19.330 --> 00:26:23.320 align:middle line:84%
We had the kitchen
staff, the galley staff,

00:26:23.320 --> 00:26:25.660 align:middle line:84%
which was basically
civilian contractors, who

00:26:25.660 --> 00:26:27.100 align:middle line:90%
would come in and service.

00:26:27.100 --> 00:26:30.789 align:middle line:84%
Food would rotate out about
every three or four weeks.

00:26:30.789 --> 00:26:32.830 align:middle line:84%
So they had a rotation
that was about every month

00:26:32.830 --> 00:26:33.746 align:middle line:90%
or a month and a half.

00:26:33.746 --> 00:26:37.570 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Was there
anybody born on the moon?

00:26:37.570 --> 00:26:40.540 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: Not that I could
say personally aware of.

00:26:40.540 --> 00:26:42.436 align:middle line:84%
I wouldn't be surprised
if at some point

00:26:42.436 --> 00:26:44.060 align:middle line:84%
that was a scientific
experiment that--

00:26:44.060 --> 00:26:46.390 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Because that would
be truly an extraterrestrial.

00:26:46.390 --> 00:26:47.598 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: Right, it would be.

00:26:47.598 --> 00:26:48.760 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, absolutely.

00:26:48.760 --> 00:26:50.650 align:middle line:84%
I know that they,
the colonies on Mars,

00:26:50.650 --> 00:26:53.530 align:middle line:84%
have had people actually
born on Mars since then

00:26:53.530 --> 00:26:56.586 align:middle line:90%
who then are Earth transplants.

00:26:56.586 --> 00:26:58.210 align:middle line:84%
But if they're born
there, then they're

00:26:58.210 --> 00:26:59.170 align:middle line:90%
not Earthlings anymore--

00:26:59.170 --> 00:26:59.690 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: They're martians.

00:26:59.690 --> 00:27:01.400 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: --they're
human martians.

00:27:01.400 --> 00:27:02.483 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: They're martians.

00:27:02.483 --> 00:27:04.935 align:middle line:84%
I wonder if they're considered
citizens of this planet?

00:27:04.935 --> 00:27:06.310 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: They
are not considered

00:27:06.310 --> 00:27:07.490 align:middle line:90%
terrestrial citizens.

00:27:07.490 --> 00:27:09.850 align:middle line:84%
They're considered citizens
of the Mars colonies.

00:27:09.850 --> 00:27:12.470 align:middle line:84%
And because of the gravity,
they can never come back here.

00:27:12.470 --> 00:27:13.270 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: All right.

00:27:13.270 --> 00:27:17.030 align:middle line:84%
Let's move on to
Mars for a second.

00:27:17.030 --> 00:27:19.220 align:middle line:84%
When you started going
to Mars, did they

00:27:19.220 --> 00:27:21.170 align:middle line:84%
have a fully equipped
base at the time

00:27:21.170 --> 00:27:23.070 align:middle line:84%
or were you in its
infancy as well?

00:27:23.070 --> 00:27:23.870 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: Oh no.

00:27:23.870 --> 00:27:26.330 align:middle line:84%
I would say that everything
had been well developed.

00:27:26.330 --> 00:27:28.340 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I felt like
when I showed up there

00:27:28.340 --> 00:27:32.010 align:middle line:84%
I was showed up in the middle
of a well oiled machine

00:27:32.010 --> 00:27:32.810 align:middle line:90%
operation--

00:27:32.810 --> 00:27:33.685 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Ready to go.

00:27:33.685 --> 00:27:36.582 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: --going on for
years before I got there.

00:27:36.582 --> 00:27:38.540 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: What's the
advantage of being on Mars?

00:27:38.540 --> 00:27:40.744 align:middle line:90%
What are they doing there?

00:27:40.744 --> 00:27:43.160 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: I don't know about
the advantage but they trying

00:27:43.160 --> 00:27:45.860 align:middle line:84%
to sustain and defend
the colonies, which

00:27:45.860 --> 00:27:47.450 align:middle line:90%
I can't say I know much about.

00:27:47.450 --> 00:27:49.460 align:middle line:84%
We never got to go to
the colonies or see them.

00:27:49.460 --> 00:27:51.110 align:middle line:84%
We were kept very
separate from them.

00:27:51.110 --> 00:27:54.740 align:middle line:84%
My understanding
is the colonies are

00:27:54.740 --> 00:27:59.060 align:middle line:84%
engaged in mining operations,
agricultural operations.

00:27:59.060 --> 00:28:00.440 align:middle line:84%
Basically anything
and everything

00:28:00.440 --> 00:28:03.830 align:middle line:84%
that a colony would want to
do to say both self-sufficient

00:28:03.830 --> 00:28:07.010 align:middle line:84%
and to be able to create
enough excess of something

00:28:07.010 --> 00:28:11.060 align:middle line:84%
to trade back to the planet
or somewhere else for profits.

00:28:11.060 --> 00:28:13.302 align:middle line:84%
Because these have to be
financially profitable

00:28:13.302 --> 00:28:15.260 align:middle line:84%
ventures, according to
the financial people who

00:28:15.260 --> 00:28:16.940 align:middle line:90%
are in charge of them.

00:28:16.940 --> 00:28:19.550 align:middle line:84%
But as a military
operative, our job

00:28:19.550 --> 00:28:22.670 align:middle line:84%
was simply to occupy the
base in which we occupied

00:28:22.670 --> 00:28:25.580 align:middle line:84%
and to patrol and defend
or protect a certain grid

00:28:25.580 --> 00:28:28.220 align:middle line:84%
territory that was on our
map to defend and protect.

00:28:28.220 --> 00:28:29.810 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Are other
countries there?

00:28:29.810 --> 00:28:31.370 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: Absolutely, yeah.

00:28:31.370 --> 00:28:35.840 align:middle line:84%
I would say what they used
to call the G8 countries,

00:28:35.840 --> 00:28:37.790 align:middle line:84%
I would say that
list of countries

00:28:37.790 --> 00:28:39.980 align:middle line:84%
there are personnel from
all of those countries

00:28:39.980 --> 00:28:43.840 align:middle line:84%
that are at some point in
part of the covert military--

00:28:43.840 --> 00:28:45.716 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Did we
bring them along?

00:28:45.716 --> 00:28:46.840 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: Yeah, absolutely.

00:28:46.840 --> 00:28:48.800 align:middle line:90%
I mean, those people--

00:28:48.800 --> 00:28:53.930 align:middle line:84%
my understanding is that
each country who participates

00:28:53.930 --> 00:28:56.210 align:middle line:90%
takes personnel in a "parcel."

00:28:56.210 --> 00:29:00.080 align:middle line:84%
and that parcel is then handed
over in a stack of paperwork

00:29:00.080 --> 00:29:03.140 align:middle line:84%
to covert military space
program activities.

00:29:03.140 --> 00:29:05.480 align:middle line:84%
Some bureaucrat, some
low level officers,

00:29:05.480 --> 00:29:08.150 align:middle line:84%
junior officers at
Lunar Operations Command

00:29:08.150 --> 00:29:10.730 align:middle line:84%
get that stack of paperwork
on what that personnel is.

00:29:10.730 --> 00:29:13.409 align:middle line:84%
And then their job is to
assign those personnel

00:29:13.409 --> 00:29:15.200 align:middle line:84%
to the various positions
within the program

00:29:15.200 --> 00:29:16.910 align:middle line:84%
that they need to
put bodies into.

00:29:16.910 --> 00:29:19.580 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: At any given time,
because of space and distance,

00:29:19.580 --> 00:29:21.640 align:middle line:90%
how long were you on Mars?

00:29:21.640 --> 00:29:23.250 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: A little
over 17 years.

00:29:23.250 --> 00:29:24.805 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: 17-- straight?

00:29:24.805 --> 00:29:26.060 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: Yeah, continuous.

00:29:26.060 --> 00:29:26.670 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, absolutely.

00:29:26.670 --> 00:29:27.470 align:middle line:90%
I lived there.

00:29:27.470 --> 00:29:30.706 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You were on Mars
for 17 straight years?

00:29:30.706 --> 00:29:32.455 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: 17 years,
three months, 14 days.

00:29:32.455 --> 00:29:36.140 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Did it feel
like a prison sentence?

00:29:36.140 --> 00:29:37.070 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: No.

00:29:37.070 --> 00:29:38.770 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it didn't
feel like that.

00:29:38.770 --> 00:29:41.874 align:middle line:84%
It felt like a lengthy
deployment, you know?

00:29:41.874 --> 00:29:43.290 align:middle line:84%
It felt like this
is where we were

00:29:43.290 --> 00:29:44.670 align:middle line:90%
going to be for a long time.

00:29:44.670 --> 00:29:46.380 align:middle line:84%
I'd say after the
first few years,

00:29:46.380 --> 00:29:47.840 align:middle line:84%
we were pretty
acclimated that this

00:29:47.840 --> 00:29:51.020 align:middle line:84%
is just what we were going
to do until we were not

00:29:51.020 --> 00:29:53.690 align:middle line:84%
doing it anymore, until we
either dead or got sent back.

00:29:53.690 --> 00:29:55.730 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Did you have a salary?

00:29:55.730 --> 00:29:58.640 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: I was supposed to
be accruing a salary that

00:29:58.640 --> 00:30:00.116 align:middle line:84%
was supposed to
go into an account

00:30:00.116 --> 00:30:01.490 align:middle line:84%
that I was supposed
to get later.

00:30:01.490 --> 00:30:03.140 align:middle line:84%
But that turns out
to be sort of a lie

00:30:03.140 --> 00:30:04.400 align:middle line:84%
that they tell
everybody because--

00:30:04.400 --> 00:30:05.566 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: So you got nothing?

00:30:05.566 --> 00:30:06.870 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: Got nothing.

00:30:06.870 --> 00:30:08.160 align:middle line:90%
(WHISPERS) Nothing.

00:30:08.160 --> 00:30:12.090 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You were on
Mars for 17 years--

00:30:12.090 --> 00:30:14.070 align:middle line:84%
of course you didn't
have to worry about rent.

00:30:14.070 --> 00:30:14.610 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: No.

00:30:14.610 --> 00:30:15.750 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Food was provided.

00:30:15.750 --> 00:30:17.979 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: Yeah, and health care.

00:30:17.979 --> 00:30:19.770 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And you thought
you were earning--

00:30:19.770 --> 00:30:22.350 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: Accruing the paycheck
that was going into an account.

00:30:22.350 --> 00:30:24.540 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: That you figured you
would have how much by the time

00:30:24.540 --> 00:30:25.340 align:middle line:90%
you came back?

00:30:25.340 --> 00:30:27.510 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: Oh, it
should have been--

00:30:27.510 --> 00:30:28.680 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: A million dollars.

00:30:28.680 --> 00:30:30.360 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: --well over a
million dollars, yeah.

00:30:30.360 --> 00:30:31.250 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: And you had nothing?

00:30:31.250 --> 00:30:31.790 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: I got nothing.

00:30:31.790 --> 00:30:33.040 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Did you feel cheated?

00:30:33.040 --> 00:30:35.206 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: Well, since I
couldn't remember right away

00:30:35.206 --> 00:30:36.670 align:middle line:90%
I didn't feel anything about it.

00:30:36.670 --> 00:30:38.520 align:middle line:84%
But once I started to
remember the process,

00:30:38.520 --> 00:30:40.990 align:middle line:84%
I got pretty angry about
being cheated in that process.

00:30:40.990 --> 00:30:42.660 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Are they
stiffing everybody?

00:30:42.660 --> 00:30:43.701 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: Oh, absolutely.

00:30:43.701 --> 00:30:46.380 align:middle line:84%
It's how they save money by not
paying their person-- there's

00:30:46.380 --> 00:30:50.360 align:middle line:84%
essentially this very
quasi gray line with what's

00:30:50.360 --> 00:30:52.000 align:middle line:90%
slavery and not slavery.

00:30:52.000 --> 00:30:53.580 align:middle line:84%
Which is another
thing that a lot

00:30:53.580 --> 00:30:55.740 align:middle line:84%
of our extraterrestrial
friends are unhappy about.

00:30:55.740 --> 00:30:58.800 align:middle line:84%
Because there are
other worlds that we

00:30:58.800 --> 00:31:02.430 align:middle line:84%
have agreements and treaties
with who think that slavery

00:31:02.430 --> 00:31:05.100 align:middle line:84%
is essentially an amoral
unethical activity.

00:31:05.100 --> 00:31:07.080 align:middle line:84%
And that we have
treaties and contracts

00:31:07.080 --> 00:31:09.700 align:middle line:84%
signed that we're not supposed
to engage in acts of slavery.

00:31:09.700 --> 00:31:12.750 align:middle line:84%
So as long as we're doing
things that are quasi slavery,

00:31:12.750 --> 00:31:14.550 align:middle line:84%
then we have these
disagreements about what

00:31:14.550 --> 00:31:15.466 align:middle line:90%
we're supposed to do--

00:31:15.466 --> 00:31:18.810 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: So we're disclosing for
the first time on this program

00:31:18.810 --> 00:31:24.037 align:middle line:84%
that the Secret Space Program
isn't paying its employees.

00:31:24.037 --> 00:31:25.370 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: A vast number of them.

00:31:25.370 --> 00:31:26.850 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, a vast number
of them are being

00:31:26.850 --> 00:31:28.683 align:middle line:84%
told that they're going
to be paid, are told

00:31:28.683 --> 00:31:30.960 align:middle line:84%
going to be paid later,
going to be told that they're

00:31:30.960 --> 00:31:34.210 align:middle line:84%
going to get rotated back, get
a nice cushy job with a pension.

00:31:34.210 --> 00:31:35.010 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Sue them.

00:31:35.010 --> 00:31:35.910 align:middle line:90%
Can you?

00:31:35.910 --> 00:31:39.630 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: Well, I'm in a process
with my congressman's office

00:31:39.630 --> 00:31:44.760 align:middle line:84%
to get paperwork, to get
papers, to get documents.

00:31:44.760 --> 00:31:47.950 align:middle line:84%
And what should, at some
point, end up probably

00:31:47.950 --> 00:31:48.750 align:middle line:90%
in a settlement.

00:31:48.750 --> 00:31:50.210 align:middle line:84%
But that's just going
to take a while.

00:31:50.210 --> 00:31:51.630 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: It'll be
sealed, you know that?

00:31:51.630 --> 00:31:52.900 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: Oh, I'm
fine with that.

00:31:52.900 --> 00:31:55.320 align:middle line:84%
I really don't care if you
know they take me into a room

00:31:55.320 --> 00:31:56.819 align:middle line:84%
and say, here, you
can look at this.

00:31:56.819 --> 00:31:57.800 align:middle line:90%
Here, we'll give you--

00:31:57.800 --> 00:31:58.620 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Here's your check.

00:31:58.620 --> 00:32:00.090 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: --but you can't
ever talk about this.

00:32:00.090 --> 00:32:00.890 align:middle line:90%
I'm fine with that.

00:32:00.890 --> 00:32:03.600 align:middle line:84%
I understand the protocols
and I'm fine with that.

00:32:03.600 --> 00:32:05.910 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Well, you must
be driving them crazy now.

00:32:05.910 --> 00:32:07.080 align:middle line:90%
Talking about this--

00:32:07.080 --> 00:32:09.390 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: I know that
some people are perfectly

00:32:09.390 --> 00:32:11.196 align:middle line:84%
happy with what I'm
doing because they know

00:32:11.196 --> 00:32:12.570 align:middle line:84%
it needs to be
discussed and they

00:32:12.570 --> 00:32:14.790 align:middle line:84%
know that there's other
people who absolutely

00:32:14.790 --> 00:32:15.930 align:middle line:90%
hate my guts for doing it.

00:32:15.930 --> 00:32:17.700 align:middle line:90%
So you know, whatever.

00:32:17.700 --> 00:32:19.710 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Tell me
about Tony Rodriguez.

00:32:19.710 --> 00:32:21.662 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: Nice guy.

00:32:21.662 --> 00:32:22.620 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Whistleblower?

00:32:22.620 --> 00:32:23.828 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: I've spoken to him.

00:32:23.828 --> 00:32:25.770 align:middle line:84%
He seems like a
really nice guy and he

00:32:25.770 --> 00:32:29.190 align:middle line:84%
has a way of recollecting
his version of events that

00:32:29.190 --> 00:32:31.050 align:middle line:84%
seem incredibly
legitimate, to me,

00:32:31.050 --> 00:32:34.560 align:middle line:84%
that recall events that
seem beyond his ability

00:32:34.560 --> 00:32:36.390 align:middle line:90%
to fabricate them.

00:32:36.390 --> 00:32:40.680 align:middle line:84%
And certainly he has discussed
a few different things

00:32:40.680 --> 00:32:45.150 align:middle line:84%
that I have also experienced
that make his recollections

00:32:45.150 --> 00:32:46.584 align:middle line:84%
seem completely
legitimate to me.

00:32:46.584 --> 00:32:48.000 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I'll have
you verify what

00:32:48.000 --> 00:32:51.000 align:middle line:84%
we're about to see with Michael
Salla and Tony Rodriguez.

00:32:51.000 --> 00:32:52.755 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: Sure.

00:32:52.755 --> 00:32:54.880 align:middle line:10%
>>TONY ROGRIGUES: But I
got lost and I saw two guys

00:32:54.880 --> 00:32:57.910 align:middle line:10%
in a military uniform
but they were aliens.

00:32:57.910 --> 00:33:01.330 align:middle line:10%
One guy was like, I want
to say he looked like a cat

00:33:01.330 --> 00:33:02.330 align:middle line:10%
but it wasn't the case.

00:33:02.330 --> 00:33:05.320 align:middle line:10%
He had coarse, orange hair.

00:33:05.320 --> 00:33:07.960 align:middle line:84%
He was shorter and
stocky and he had--

00:33:07.960 --> 00:33:09.220 align:middle line:90%
he was ugly looking.

00:33:09.220 --> 00:33:10.264 align:middle line:90%
He was ugly.

00:33:10.264 --> 00:33:12.430 align:middle line:10%
I really don't know how to
describe other than that.

00:33:12.430 --> 00:33:13.360 align:middle line:10%
He had hair.

00:33:13.360 --> 00:33:16.960 align:middle line:10%
And the other guy was smaller.

00:33:16.960 --> 00:33:18.400 align:middle line:10%
And he was more of a fish.

00:33:18.400 --> 00:33:21.995 align:middle line:10%
He had like a fish
eyes and a snout.

00:33:21.995 --> 00:33:22.870 align:middle line:10%
You know what I mean?

00:33:22.870 --> 00:33:23.590 align:middle line:10%
And they were together.

00:33:23.590 --> 00:33:25.423 align:middle line:10%
And I walked-- because
they were in uniform,

00:33:25.423 --> 00:33:29.530 align:middle line:10%
I thought that they were
in the army, like I was

00:33:29.530 --> 00:33:30.990 align:middle line:10%
or whatever I was in.

00:33:30.990 --> 00:33:31.790 align:middle line:10%
The fleet.

00:33:31.790 --> 00:33:32.710 align:middle line:10%
I thought they were
part of the fleet.

00:33:32.710 --> 00:33:33.830 align:middle line:10%
So I asked them, I'm lost.

00:33:33.830 --> 00:33:34.871 align:middle line:10%
Can you guys help me out?

00:33:34.871 --> 00:33:37.030 align:middle line:10%
And they said--

00:33:37.030 --> 00:33:38.740 align:middle line:10%
I had to wear a
collar, a slave collar,

00:33:38.740 --> 00:33:40.180 align:middle line:10%
there was a correction collar.

00:33:40.180 --> 00:33:44.870 align:middle line:10%
And you would get electrified
if you were disciplined.

00:33:44.870 --> 00:33:46.870 align:middle line:10%
And they saw my collar
and he said, what are you

00:33:46.870 --> 00:33:47.530 align:middle line:10%
doing talking to us?

00:33:47.530 --> 00:33:48.446 align:middle line:10%
Don't even talk to us.

00:33:48.446 --> 00:33:49.570 align:middle line:10%
How are you even out here?

00:33:49.570 --> 00:33:50.994 align:middle line:10%
You don't have money.

00:33:50.994 --> 00:33:52.660 align:middle line:10%
And they were-- what
are you doing here?

00:33:52.660 --> 00:33:54.370 align:middle line:84%
They immediately--
what makes you

00:33:54.370 --> 00:33:55.890 align:middle line:90%
think we're going to help you?

00:33:55.890 --> 00:33:58.750 align:middle line:10%
And it was a telepathic
communication.

00:33:58.750 --> 00:34:00.250 align:middle line:10%
And I said, I'm lost.

00:34:00.250 --> 00:34:03.514 align:middle line:10%
Can you just tell me how to
get back to the hangar area?

00:34:03.514 --> 00:34:05.680 align:middle line:10%
And they said you can't
even get to the hangar area.

00:34:05.680 --> 00:34:06.710 align:middle line:10%
Guys like, you don't
even have money.

00:34:06.710 --> 00:34:08.090 align:middle line:10%
I said, I've got money.

00:34:08.090 --> 00:34:11.350 align:middle line:10%
And as soon as I showed them
my money, the one punched me.

00:34:11.350 --> 00:34:13.929 align:middle line:10%
And they basically beat
me up and took my money.

00:34:13.929 --> 00:34:15.534 align:middle line:90%
I got mugged.

00:34:15.534 --> 00:34:16.360 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Geez.

00:34:16.360 --> 00:34:17.650 align:middle line:90%
What do you think of that?

00:34:17.650 --> 00:34:19.280 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: That sounds like
a legitimate experience.

00:34:19.280 --> 00:34:19.750 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: It does?

00:34:19.750 --> 00:34:20.980 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: It does,
it absolutely does.

00:34:20.980 --> 00:34:22.479 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Now, he
called the ET ugly.

00:34:22.479 --> 00:34:24.340 align:middle line:84%
Beauty is in the
eyes of the beholder.

00:34:24.340 --> 00:34:24.610 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: Absolutely.

00:34:24.610 --> 00:34:25.989 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: They probably
thought he was ugly.

00:34:25.989 --> 00:34:27.699 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: I'm sure
that they did, yeah,

00:34:27.699 --> 00:34:29.679 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: But these
things are happening

00:34:29.679 --> 00:34:30.889 align:middle line:90%
the way he described it?

00:34:30.889 --> 00:34:32.679 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: I would suggest that.

00:34:32.679 --> 00:34:35.139 align:middle line:84%
One of the-- probably the
most interesting things

00:34:35.139 --> 00:34:38.260 align:middle line:84%
that I got to do when I was
stationed on the Nautilus

00:34:38.260 --> 00:34:40.210 align:middle line:84%
was go on to
diplomatic missions.

00:34:40.210 --> 00:34:42.980 align:middle line:84%
And diplomatic missions to the
intergalactic space station

00:34:42.980 --> 00:34:44.980 align:middle line:84%
that orbits around Jupiter,
which is essentially

00:34:44.980 --> 00:34:50.139 align:middle line:84%
a diplomatic meeting area
for hundreds of species

00:34:50.139 --> 00:34:52.239 align:middle line:90%
and us and them.

00:34:52.239 --> 00:34:53.710 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: How many did you meet?

00:34:53.710 --> 00:34:55.835 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: Me personally,
I would say several dozen.

00:34:55.835 --> 00:34:56.635 align:middle line:90%
See?

00:34:56.635 --> 00:34:57.520 align:middle line:90%
Hundreds.

00:34:57.520 --> 00:35:00.670 align:middle line:84%
Because the main meeting room
is this large room that's

00:35:00.670 --> 00:35:03.850 align:middle line:84%
like, several hundred
meters wide with Florida

00:35:03.850 --> 00:35:07.630 align:middle line:84%
ceilings probably, 70 or 80 feet
high with I want to say glass.

00:35:07.630 --> 00:35:09.659 align:middle line:84%
But it probably wasn't
silicon glass windows

00:35:09.659 --> 00:35:11.200 align:middle line:84%
that went all the
way around that you

00:35:11.200 --> 00:35:12.300 align:middle line:90%
had this amazing view of.

00:35:12.300 --> 00:35:14.021 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Do they
all look different?

00:35:14.021 --> 00:35:15.520 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: As varied
and different as

00:35:15.520 --> 00:35:16.420 align:middle line:90%
you can possibly say.

00:35:16.420 --> 00:35:18.450 align:middle line:84%
I would say the smallest
extraterrestrial

00:35:18.450 --> 00:35:21.010 align:middle line:84%
I ever saw was probably
about 18, 24 inches high

00:35:21.010 --> 00:35:23.380 align:middle line:84%
and the largest one was
probably 60 feet tall.

00:35:23.380 --> 00:35:24.770 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: 60 feet tall?

00:35:24.770 --> 00:35:25.600 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: Yeah,
about 60 feet tall.

00:35:25.600 --> 00:35:26.400 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:35:26.400 --> 00:35:27.850 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Did it look human?

00:35:27.850 --> 00:35:32.060 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: Humanoid in the
sense two arms, two legs--

00:35:32.060 --> 00:35:32.860 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Nose?

00:35:32.860 --> 00:35:35.260 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: --bipedal.

00:35:35.260 --> 00:35:38.300 align:middle line:84%
You could certainly
identify it by looking at it

00:35:38.300 --> 00:35:40.310 align:middle line:84%
but I wouldn't say that
it just looked like you

00:35:40.310 --> 00:35:41.650 align:middle line:90%
or I 60 feet tall.

00:35:41.650 --> 00:35:44.410 align:middle line:84%
It had some other sort of
distinguishing features.

00:35:44.410 --> 00:35:48.040 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And would you say the
ETs were all benevolent or not?

00:35:48.040 --> 00:35:50.890 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: In that particular
location, everyone who's there

00:35:50.890 --> 00:35:53.080 align:middle line:84%
is there to have a
conversation about trade,

00:35:53.080 --> 00:35:55.330 align:middle line:90%
contracts, negotiations.

00:35:55.330 --> 00:35:57.130 align:middle line:84%
So everyone's on
their best behavior.

00:35:57.130 --> 00:35:58.420 align:middle line:90%
Everyone's being nice.

00:35:58.420 --> 00:36:02.620 align:middle line:84%
It's usually not a bunch
of grunts arguing about.

00:36:02.620 --> 00:36:03.770 align:middle line:90%
It's diplomats.

00:36:03.770 --> 00:36:04.570 align:middle line:90%
It's officers.

00:36:04.570 --> 00:36:08.020 align:middle line:84%
It's people out of
various ambassadorial

00:36:08.020 --> 00:36:10.060 align:middle line:84%
or diplomatic corps
having conversations.

00:36:10.060 --> 00:36:11.906 align:middle line:84%
So everyone's pretty
cordial there.

00:36:11.906 --> 00:36:13.030 align:middle line:90%
Everyone is pretty cordial.

00:36:13.030 --> 00:36:18.765 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Captain Cramer, do
you wake up sweating and upset?

00:36:18.765 --> 00:36:20.390 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: I used to
have night terrors.

00:36:20.390 --> 00:36:21.230 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, I used to.

00:36:21.230 --> 00:36:22.646 align:middle line:84%
I don't have them
so much anymore.

00:36:22.646 --> 00:36:25.369 align:middle line:84%
Lots of therapy has gotten
me to an OK place where I

00:36:25.369 --> 00:36:26.660 align:middle line:90%
can talk about a lot of things.

00:36:26.660 --> 00:36:29.330 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Have you ever gone
to psychiatric counseling?

00:36:29.330 --> 00:36:30.455 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: Sure, absolutely.

00:36:30.455 --> 00:36:31.970 align:middle line:90%
And I've gone to counseling.

00:36:31.970 --> 00:36:33.540 align:middle line:84%
I went to a psychiatrist
for a while.

00:36:33.540 --> 00:36:35.300 align:middle line:90%
Oh yeah, absolutely.

00:36:35.300 --> 00:36:37.320 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Medication?

00:36:37.320 --> 00:36:39.486 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: Antidepressants,
anti-anxiety medication

00:36:39.486 --> 00:36:42.110 align:middle line:84%
for a little while to deal with
the depression and the anxiety,

00:36:42.110 --> 00:36:43.097 align:middle line:90%
yeah.

00:36:43.097 --> 00:36:44.180 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: You off that now?

00:36:44.180 --> 00:36:46.470 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: Oh yeah, for years.

00:36:46.470 --> 00:36:48.690 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: How many people
do you think come out

00:36:48.690 --> 00:36:51.540 align:middle line:90%
of these programs the same way?

00:36:51.540 --> 00:36:53.970 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: I would say
that most people come out

00:36:53.970 --> 00:36:57.600 align:middle line:84%
of these programs having had
a series of experiences that

00:36:57.600 --> 00:37:01.260 align:middle line:84%
have either shocked them,
traumatized them, or unnerved

00:37:01.260 --> 00:37:04.140 align:middle line:84%
them in a way that
they're psychologically

00:37:04.140 --> 00:37:05.330 align:middle line:90%
unsteady because of it.

00:37:05.330 --> 00:37:06.980 align:middle line:84%
And it takes a
certain amount of just

00:37:06.980 --> 00:37:08.730 align:middle line:84%
going through some
kind of healing process

00:37:08.730 --> 00:37:11.070 align:middle line:84%
to get to be able to where
you can feel stable again.

00:37:11.070 --> 00:37:12.736 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You served
in the Marine Corps.

00:37:12.736 --> 00:37:13.770 align:middle line:90%
You took an oath.

00:37:13.770 --> 00:37:15.060 align:middle line:90%
I served in the Navy.

00:37:15.060 --> 00:37:16.100 align:middle line:90%
I took an oath.

00:37:16.100 --> 00:37:18.745 align:middle line:84%
And we feel as if we've
done things for country.

00:37:18.745 --> 00:37:19.620 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: Absolutely.

00:37:19.620 --> 00:37:22.500 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Do you think,
being in these programs,

00:37:22.500 --> 00:37:24.930 align:middle line:84%
you've done something
for our country

00:37:24.930 --> 00:37:27.365 align:middle line:90%
or do you feel used and abused?

00:37:27.365 --> 00:37:28.740 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: I know
that my oath was

00:37:28.740 --> 00:37:30.780 align:middle line:84%
to protect my
planet and my people

00:37:30.780 --> 00:37:34.020 align:middle line:84%
from anything and everything
that could do it harm.

00:37:34.020 --> 00:37:35.700 align:middle line:84%
And so in that sense
I feel like I've

00:37:35.700 --> 00:37:38.830 align:middle line:84%
done my job, that I did
what I was supposed to do.

00:37:38.830 --> 00:37:43.020 align:middle line:84%
I certainly feel
taken advantage by

00:37:43.020 --> 00:37:44.640 align:middle line:84%
the bureaucratic's
in the system.

00:37:44.640 --> 00:37:48.870 align:middle line:84%
I feel that my military
commanders did their best

00:37:48.870 --> 00:37:51.270 align:middle line:84%
to train me the best
that they could,

00:37:51.270 --> 00:37:53.820 align:middle line:84%
to treat me that the best they
could with respect and dignity

00:37:53.820 --> 00:37:57.040 align:middle line:84%
and honor and that
they continue to do so.

00:37:57.040 --> 00:37:58.560 align:middle line:84%
But there is
definitely a disconnect

00:37:58.560 --> 00:38:02.190 align:middle line:84%
between what certain military
personnel think should happen

00:38:02.190 --> 00:38:04.110 align:middle line:84%
and what is OK and the
way to treat people

00:38:04.110 --> 00:38:06.694 align:middle line:84%
and the way certain members of
the bureaucratic administrative

00:38:06.694 --> 00:38:08.360 align:middle line:84%
part think that it's
OK to treat people.

00:38:08.360 --> 00:38:10.140 align:middle line:84%
There's a major
disconnect there for sure.

00:38:10.140 --> 00:38:11.650 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Do you have children?

00:38:11.650 --> 00:38:12.460 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: None at this time.

00:38:12.460 --> 00:38:13.260 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: All right.

00:38:13.260 --> 00:38:15.510 align:middle line:84%
If you did, would you
want them in this program?

00:38:15.510 --> 00:38:20.531 align:middle line:90%


00:38:20.531 --> 00:38:21.780 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: That's a tough call.

00:38:21.780 --> 00:38:23.730 align:middle line:84%
On the one hand, I
wouldn't necessarily

00:38:23.730 --> 00:38:25.450 align:middle line:84%
want them to have
my experiences.

00:38:25.450 --> 00:38:26.250 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Right.

00:38:26.250 --> 00:38:30.430 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: On the
other hand, I would

00:38:30.430 --> 00:38:34.000 align:middle line:84%
have to say that if that
was their destiny, to have

00:38:34.000 --> 00:38:35.920 align:middle line:84%
to go through that,
then I would just

00:38:35.920 --> 00:38:38.620 align:middle line:84%
want to be the best parent in
the world to try and support

00:38:38.620 --> 00:38:41.110 align:middle line:84%
them in that process and their
recovery in that process.

00:38:41.110 --> 00:38:45.160 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Would you go through
what you went through again?

00:38:45.160 --> 00:38:47.920 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: Not voluntarily.

00:38:47.920 --> 00:38:48.765 align:middle line:90%
No, not voluntarily.

00:38:48.765 --> 00:38:50.056 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: What if they take you?

00:38:50.056 --> 00:38:51.850 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: But at
the same time, I

00:38:51.850 --> 00:38:53.890 align:middle line:84%
can't look back at
those experiences

00:38:53.890 --> 00:38:56.840 align:middle line:84%
and say I wouldn't want them
as part of my life experience.

00:38:56.840 --> 00:39:00.460 align:middle line:84%
They make me who I
am and they certainly

00:39:00.460 --> 00:39:02.230 align:middle line:84%
are the best and the
worst of everything

00:39:02.230 --> 00:39:03.380 align:middle line:90%
that I've ever experienced.

00:39:03.380 --> 00:39:04.970 align:middle line:90%
So that's a tough one.

00:39:04.970 --> 00:39:07.150 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I wouldn't necessarily
go back and say yeah,

00:39:07.150 --> 00:39:08.530 align:middle line:90%
I volunteer to do this again.

00:39:08.530 --> 00:39:10.446 align:middle line:84%
But I wouldn't go back
and take it away either

00:39:10.446 --> 00:39:12.545 align:middle line:84%
because there's too much
value as a human being

00:39:12.545 --> 00:39:14.170 align:middle line:84%
that I've gained from
those experiences

00:39:14.170 --> 00:39:15.109 align:middle line:90%
to want to undo them.

00:39:15.109 --> 00:39:16.900 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: What would
your commanding officer

00:39:16.900 --> 00:39:18.670 align:middle line:90%
say once he sees this interview?

00:39:18.670 --> 00:39:19.990 align:middle line:90%
Would he go, right on, Randy.

00:39:19.990 --> 00:39:22.480 align:middle line:84%
You got the message out
that we wanted you to.

00:39:22.480 --> 00:39:23.710 align:middle line:90%
Or you said too much?

00:39:23.710 --> 00:39:24.940 align:middle line:90%
What would he say?

00:39:24.940 --> 00:39:28.150 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: He's made it very
clear that as the spokesperson

00:39:28.150 --> 00:39:31.090 align:middle line:84%
it's my job to just speak
clearly and honestly

00:39:31.090 --> 00:39:32.170 align:middle line:90%
and truthful.

00:39:32.170 --> 00:39:34.840 align:middle line:84%
And that it's not
up for anybody else

00:39:34.840 --> 00:39:37.409 align:middle line:84%
to judge whether I'm doing
the right job or not.

00:39:37.409 --> 00:39:38.950 align:middle line:84%
The first couple of
interviews that I

00:39:38.950 --> 00:39:43.220 align:middle line:84%
did, I remember discussing
this with him and asking him,

00:39:43.220 --> 00:39:44.810 align:middle line:90%
you know did I do OK?

00:39:44.810 --> 00:39:46.840 align:middle line:90%
And he kind of hemmed and hawed.

00:39:46.840 --> 00:39:47.950 align:middle line:90%
And I was like, what?

00:39:47.950 --> 00:39:48.750 align:middle line:90%
What did I not do?

00:39:48.750 --> 00:39:51.220 align:middle line:84%
He's like, well, you kind
of softballed a little bit.

00:39:51.220 --> 00:39:52.970 align:middle line:84%
And I said, what do
you mean I softballed?

00:39:52.970 --> 00:39:55.950 align:middle line:90%
And he said, well, you kind of--

00:39:55.950 --> 00:39:57.990 align:middle line:84%
you went out there
not really being you.

00:39:57.990 --> 00:40:00.570 align:middle line:84%
And I was like, oh, you mean
you want me to sort of curse

00:40:00.570 --> 00:40:02.640 align:middle line:84%
and swear, yell and
scream some more?

00:40:02.640 --> 00:40:04.979 align:middle line:84%
And he was like, well, if
that's you then be you.

00:40:04.979 --> 00:40:07.020 align:middle line:84%
He said, I don't want you
to go out there and put

00:40:07.020 --> 00:40:08.490 align:middle line:90%
on a presentation for people.

00:40:08.490 --> 00:40:10.110 align:middle line:84%
I want you to go out there
and tell people the truth

00:40:10.110 --> 00:40:10.910 align:middle line:90%
and be you.

00:40:10.910 --> 00:40:12.960 align:middle line:84%
So I felt like the first
couple of interviews

00:40:12.960 --> 00:40:14.990 align:middle line:84%
that I did I was trying
to be a little stiffer--

00:40:14.990 --> 00:40:15.790 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Sure.

00:40:15.790 --> 00:40:15.950 align:middle line:90%


00:40:15.950 --> 00:40:17.940 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: --and that
his only advice was

00:40:17.940 --> 00:40:19.620 align:middle line:90%
to just loosen up and be you.

00:40:19.620 --> 00:40:21.120 align:middle line:84%
And so the more I
feel like I'm just

00:40:21.120 --> 00:40:24.000 align:middle line:84%
being honest and being myself
than I'm doing the right thing.

00:40:24.000 --> 00:40:25.375 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Do you
miss the program?

00:40:25.375 --> 00:40:28.667 align:middle line:90%


00:40:28.667 --> 00:40:30.000 align:middle line:90%
Or does it feel good to be home?

00:40:30.000 --> 00:40:31.980 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: Oddly
enough, sometimes I do.

00:40:31.980 --> 00:40:33.840 align:middle line:90%
Oddly enough, sometimes I do.

00:40:33.840 --> 00:40:34.680 align:middle line:90%
There is a certain--

00:40:34.680 --> 00:40:36.180 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Did you
make friends there?

00:40:36.180 --> 00:40:36.930 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: Oh, absolutely.

00:40:36.930 --> 00:40:37.250 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yeah.

00:40:37.250 --> 00:40:38.670 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: Yeah, absolutely.

00:40:38.670 --> 00:40:44.220 align:middle line:84%
There is a certain certainty
about service in combat

00:40:44.220 --> 00:40:47.650 align:middle line:84%
that makes your life black
and white and clear--

00:40:47.650 --> 00:40:48.450 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Sure.

00:40:48.450 --> 00:40:49.533 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: In certain ways.

00:40:49.533 --> 00:40:52.080 align:middle line:84%
And I guess sometimes I
miss that because trying

00:40:52.080 --> 00:40:56.080 align:middle line:84%
to be and navigate civilian life
is very cloudy and very gray

00:40:56.080 --> 00:40:56.880 align:middle line:90%
sometimes.

00:40:56.880 --> 00:40:59.171 align:middle line:84%
And it's not always so clear
what you're supposed to do

00:40:59.171 --> 00:41:02.721 align:middle line:84%
or what the right thing to do is
or what choice A, B, C, D or E

00:41:02.721 --> 00:41:03.720 align:middle line:90%
you're supposed to take.

00:41:03.720 --> 00:41:06.360 align:middle line:84%
When you're serving
in a military unit,

00:41:06.360 --> 00:41:08.220 align:middle line:90%
it's much more clear.

00:41:08.220 --> 00:41:09.810 align:middle line:90%
You do this, you don't do this.

00:41:09.810 --> 00:41:11.950 align:middle line:84%
And so sometimes I miss
that simplicity, sure.

00:41:11.950 --> 00:41:13.408 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: What would
you say, Randy,

00:41:13.408 --> 00:41:15.450 align:middle line:84%
what is your best experience
either on the Moon

00:41:15.450 --> 00:41:20.220 align:middle line:84%
or on Mars that just was
so fulfilling for you?

00:41:20.220 --> 00:41:22.950 align:middle line:90%


00:41:22.950 --> 00:41:24.510 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: We were actually--

00:41:24.510 --> 00:41:31.050 align:middle line:84%
my squad and I were captured
by indigenous reptoids on Mars

00:41:31.050 --> 00:41:33.930 align:middle line:84%
and spent 5 and 1/2
months living with them.

00:41:33.930 --> 00:41:34.730 align:middle line:90%
And I would--

00:41:34.730 --> 00:41:35.460 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Captured?

00:41:35.460 --> 00:41:36.330 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: Yeah.

00:41:36.330 --> 00:41:39.000 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Like, in
their not all friendly?

00:41:39.000 --> 00:41:42.990 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: We were in a constant
state of military combat with

00:41:42.990 --> 00:41:44.340 align:middle line:90%
two indigenous species--

00:41:44.340 --> 00:41:47.400 align:middle line:84%
an insect species and
a reptoids species.

00:41:47.400 --> 00:41:51.030 align:middle line:84%
Which then got more complicated
when the Draconian invasion

00:41:51.030 --> 00:41:53.610 align:middle line:84%
occurred and then it was
a very complicated sort

00:41:53.610 --> 00:41:54.530 align:middle line:90%
of war conflict.

00:41:54.530 --> 00:41:55.530 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Was it violent?

00:41:55.530 --> 00:41:58.990 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: Very, very violent
on a very regular basis.

00:41:58.990 --> 00:42:01.209 align:middle line:84%
I mean, we were in probably
active combat engagements

00:42:01.209 --> 00:42:02.250 align:middle line:90%
every three to four days.

00:42:02.250 --> 00:42:04.110 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Did we lose personnel?

00:42:04.110 --> 00:42:05.370 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: All the time.

00:42:05.370 --> 00:42:06.420 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: And did they?

00:42:06.420 --> 00:42:08.090 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: All the time.

00:42:08.090 --> 00:42:11.139 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: What kind of
weaponry would we use?

00:42:11.139 --> 00:42:12.680 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: For soldiers
on the ground,

00:42:12.680 --> 00:42:16.340 align:middle line:84%
our primary weaponry is a
magnetic propelled rifle

00:42:16.340 --> 00:42:21.680 align:middle line:84%
or a Gauss gun or a rail gun
that fires out magnetically

00:42:21.680 --> 00:42:23.710 align:middle line:90%
propelled slugs.

00:42:23.710 --> 00:42:26.300 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And if it hits one
of these beings, what happens?

00:42:26.300 --> 00:42:28.610 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: Depending on
who it is or depending

00:42:28.610 --> 00:42:32.580 align:middle line:84%
on the size of the slug, it
usually penetrates and goes

00:42:32.580 --> 00:42:33.380 align:middle line:90%
right through them.

00:42:33.380 --> 00:42:34.889 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: And then kills them?

00:42:34.889 --> 00:42:37.430 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: Doesn't necessarily
kill them right away, depending

00:42:37.430 --> 00:42:39.080 align:middle line:90%
on their internal structure.

00:42:39.080 --> 00:42:42.260 align:middle line:84%
The indigenous reptoids had
a double circulatory system

00:42:42.260 --> 00:42:45.530 align:middle line:84%
they had two hearts with what
I would call an internal organ

00:42:45.530 --> 00:42:47.330 align:middle line:84%
circulatory system
and then a perimeter

00:42:47.330 --> 00:42:49.632 align:middle line:90%
or external circulatory system.

00:42:49.632 --> 00:42:51.590 align:middle line:84%
So you could shoot holes
in their arms and legs

00:42:51.590 --> 00:42:52.920 align:middle line:84%
and they wouldn't
lose blood pressure.

00:42:52.920 --> 00:42:54.050 align:middle line:84%
Well, they wouldn't
lose blood pressure

00:42:54.050 --> 00:42:55.440 align:middle line:90%
in their central organs.

00:42:55.440 --> 00:42:56.827 align:middle line:90%
So you really had to aim for--

00:42:56.827 --> 00:42:58.910 align:middle line:84%
you had to hit a couple
vitals in the central area

00:42:58.910 --> 00:43:00.120 align:middle line:90%
before they would go down.

00:43:00.120 --> 00:43:02.870 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: So it's violent there.

00:43:02.870 --> 00:43:04.320 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: Very.

00:43:04.320 --> 00:43:05.120 align:middle line:90%
Very.

00:43:05.120 --> 00:43:07.370 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: It's not as
friendly as one would think.

00:43:07.370 --> 00:43:10.170 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: No, it's an
incredibly violent experience.

00:43:10.170 --> 00:43:12.800 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Did you meet
any ETs you liked?

00:43:12.800 --> 00:43:14.180 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: Yeah, no, absolutely.

00:43:14.180 --> 00:43:16.740 align:middle line:84%
I mean, like I said,
when we were captured

00:43:16.740 --> 00:43:18.806 align:middle line:90%
and we actually were--

00:43:18.806 --> 00:43:20.180 align:middle line:84%
the whole purpose
wasn't you know

00:43:20.180 --> 00:43:21.759 align:middle line:90%
to torture us for five months.

00:43:21.759 --> 00:43:23.300 align:middle line:84%
The whole purpose
was actually for us

00:43:23.300 --> 00:43:24.800 align:middle line:84%
to live among them
for five months

00:43:24.800 --> 00:43:28.130 align:middle line:84%
so that we could go back
with an experience to say,

00:43:28.130 --> 00:43:29.362 align:middle line:90%
they're not all bad.

00:43:29.362 --> 00:43:30.820 align:middle line:84%
And kind of have
this conversation.

00:43:30.820 --> 00:43:32.690 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Where did
you live with them?

00:43:32.690 --> 00:43:34.430 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: In a
subterranean community.

00:43:34.430 --> 00:43:35.530 align:middle line:90%
They all live underground there.

00:43:35.530 --> 00:43:36.440 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: On the Moon or Mars?

00:43:36.440 --> 00:43:37.250 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: On Mars.

00:43:37.250 --> 00:43:38.450 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: On Mars.

00:43:38.450 --> 00:43:40.430 align:middle line:90%
In their craft?

00:43:40.430 --> 00:43:42.930 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: They have craft
but we didn't ever see them.

00:43:42.930 --> 00:43:44.240 align:middle line:90%
They didn't ever use them.

00:43:44.240 --> 00:43:48.830 align:middle line:84%
They had sort of chosen
to live in a state of what

00:43:48.830 --> 00:43:50.332 align:middle line:84%
I would say is sort
of a more chosen

00:43:50.332 --> 00:43:52.790 align:middle line:84%
primitive state than what their
technology could allow them

00:43:52.790 --> 00:43:55.929 align:middle line:84%
to do because they feel that
technology is what destroyed

00:43:55.929 --> 00:43:57.470 align:middle line:84%
their atmosphere
and nearly destroyed

00:43:57.470 --> 00:43:58.980 align:middle line:90%
their planet in the first place.

00:43:58.980 --> 00:44:01.580 align:middle line:84%
And so they were trying to
live a little bit differently.

00:44:01.580 --> 00:44:04.910 align:middle line:84%
But I would also
say that that was

00:44:04.910 --> 00:44:09.230 align:middle line:84%
specific to this
particular group, or tribe,

00:44:09.230 --> 00:44:12.290 align:middle line:84%
this community that lived
in this particular area.

00:44:12.290 --> 00:44:16.160 align:middle line:84%
That if you went global with
the indigenous reptoids,

00:44:16.160 --> 00:44:18.500 align:middle line:84%
they're not all on the
same page about that.

00:44:18.500 --> 00:44:20.000 align:middle line:84%
Depending on what
part of the planet

00:44:20.000 --> 00:44:21.500 align:middle line:84%
you landed on or
engaged with them

00:44:21.500 --> 00:44:24.040 align:middle line:84%
with would greatly
vary the experience

00:44:24.040 --> 00:44:25.290 align:middle line:90%
that you would have with them.

00:44:25.290 --> 00:44:28.020 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Can you describe
what they look like?

00:44:28.020 --> 00:44:28.820 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: Sure.

00:44:28.820 --> 00:44:32.660 align:middle line:84%
I mean, they looked like
a bipedal developed,

00:44:32.660 --> 00:44:34.400 align:middle line:84%
what I would call,
sort of a rock lizard.

00:44:34.400 --> 00:44:36.364 align:middle line:84%
So not like a crocodile
or an alligator--

00:44:36.364 --> 00:44:37.280 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Like a gecko?

00:44:37.280 --> 00:44:38.280 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: Kind of, yeah.

00:44:38.280 --> 00:44:40.220 align:middle line:84%
I mean, they would
have a shorter snout--

00:44:40.220 --> 00:44:42.360 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: The insurance
company will love this one.

00:44:42.360 --> 00:44:43.734 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: --have
a shorter snout.

00:44:43.734 --> 00:44:49.874 align:middle line:84%
They tend to have a reddish to
sandy colored skin or scales.

00:44:49.874 --> 00:44:50.790 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Walk upright?

00:44:50.790 --> 00:44:52.700 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: Would walk
upright on two legs.

00:44:52.700 --> 00:44:54.320 align:middle line:84%
But there is quite
a bit of variation

00:44:54.320 --> 00:44:56.510 align:middle line:84%
in the patterning that can
show up on their scaling.

00:44:56.510 --> 00:44:59.780 align:middle line:84%
So they often would
have black, yellow, red,

00:44:59.780 --> 00:45:02.615 align:middle line:84%
some very interesting
patterning on their scales.

00:45:02.615 --> 00:45:03.800 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Would you--

00:45:03.800 --> 00:45:05.680 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: I would
say they height

00:45:05.680 --> 00:45:09.140 align:middle line:84%
wise could vary from about 5 and
1/2 feet to almost 7 feet tall.

00:45:09.140 --> 00:45:11.300 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: How do
they communicate?

00:45:11.300 --> 00:45:13.220 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: They
communicate verbally.

00:45:13.220 --> 00:45:14.524 align:middle line:90%
They can speak.

00:45:14.524 --> 00:45:16.190 align:middle line:84%
Some of them are very
developed and they

00:45:16.190 --> 00:45:17.240 align:middle line:90%
can communicate silently.

00:45:17.240 --> 00:45:18.410 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: They have
their own language?

00:45:18.410 --> 00:45:19.340 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: Absolutely, they do.

00:45:19.340 --> 00:45:20.240 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:45:20.240 --> 00:45:23.596 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: How was
their pitched voice?

00:45:23.596 --> 00:45:25.970 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: I would say again,
that depends on the heights,

00:45:25.970 --> 00:45:26.990 align:middle line:90%
just like us.

00:45:26.990 --> 00:45:28.940 align:middle line:84%
A bigger person with
a bigger set of lungs

00:45:28.940 --> 00:45:30.606 align:middle line:84%
is going to have a
deeper voice and is--

00:45:30.606 --> 00:45:32.540 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: (HIGH PITCHED)
Not necessarily.

00:45:32.540 --> 00:45:36.230 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: But I would say
that the main variation is

00:45:36.230 --> 00:45:37.760 align:middle line:84%
in their tongue
and their palate.

00:45:37.760 --> 00:45:40.760 align:middle line:84%
So our tongue in our
pilot is a strong dictator

00:45:40.760 --> 00:45:41.857 align:middle line:90%
in how our speech sounds.

00:45:41.857 --> 00:45:43.940 align:middle line:84%
Their tongue and their
palate is a strong dictator

00:45:43.940 --> 00:45:45.650 align:middle line:90%
and how their language sounds.

00:45:45.650 --> 00:45:48.530 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: So they're not as
benevolent as one would think?

00:45:48.530 --> 00:45:50.780 align:middle line:84%
Doctor David Jacobs
may be correct

00:45:50.780 --> 00:45:55.190 align:middle line:84%
when he says there's an evil
presence with some of these.

00:45:55.190 --> 00:45:58.760 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: I would
say some of them

00:45:58.760 --> 00:46:00.332 align:middle line:84%
are more enlightened
than others.

00:46:00.332 --> 00:46:02.540 align:middle line:84%
Just like human beings, are
a little more enlightened

00:46:02.540 --> 00:46:03.340 align:middle line:90%
than others.

00:46:03.340 --> 00:46:06.250 align:middle line:84%
But like everybody, they can
have an aggressive nature

00:46:06.250 --> 00:46:07.050 align:middle line:90%
to them.

00:46:07.050 --> 00:46:08.675 align:middle line:84%
They can have a
warlike nature to them.

00:46:08.675 --> 00:46:11.090 align:middle line:84%
And you get into a
conflict with them

00:46:11.090 --> 00:46:13.640 align:middle line:84%
and they can resort to their
primal angrier or selves

00:46:13.640 --> 00:46:16.470 align:middle line:84%
just like we do in
a combat situation.

00:46:16.470 --> 00:46:19.850 align:middle line:84%
Some of the tribes are
definitely very warlike

00:46:19.850 --> 00:46:21.860 align:middle line:84%
and if you met them, you'd
probably just be food

00:46:21.860 --> 00:46:23.690 align:middle line:90%
if you couldn't win the fight.

00:46:23.690 --> 00:46:24.830 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: They eat us?

00:46:24.830 --> 00:46:25.310 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: Oh, sure.

00:46:25.310 --> 00:46:25.610 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:46:25.610 --> 00:46:27.860 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: So "The Twilight
Zone" show, To Serve Man,

00:46:27.860 --> 00:46:28.850 align:middle line:90%
was correct?

00:46:28.850 --> 00:46:31.460 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: Well, I mean they
certainly-- some of them

00:46:31.460 --> 00:46:35.420 align:middle line:84%
see us as a completely
different species, a completely

00:46:35.420 --> 00:46:36.530 align:middle line:90%
different type of animal.

00:46:36.530 --> 00:46:39.160 align:middle line:84%
And so we can certainly
be on the menu.

00:46:39.160 --> 00:46:41.600 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: How many bases
are there that we have?

00:46:41.600 --> 00:46:43.760 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: Oh, I would
say hundreds probably.

00:46:43.760 --> 00:46:44.780 align:middle line:84%
But I have no idea
the actual number.

00:46:44.780 --> 00:46:45.650 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Scattered
all over the--

00:46:45.650 --> 00:46:48.326 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: Yeah, it would easily
hundreds if not thousands

00:46:48.326 --> 00:46:49.700 align:middle line:84%
but I couldn't
give you a number.

00:46:49.700 --> 00:46:51.786 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: What about the ETs?

00:46:51.786 --> 00:46:52.910 align:middle line:90%
>>CRAMER: I would say more.

00:46:52.910 --> 00:46:55.490 align:middle line:84%
They probably have even
more bases and more stations

00:46:55.490 --> 00:46:58.400 align:middle line:84%
than we do because
there's at least three

00:46:58.400 --> 00:47:01.850 align:middle line:84%
or four intelligent
species that live on Mars.

00:47:01.850 --> 00:47:03.810 align:middle line:84%
At least three or four
that I'm aware of.

00:47:03.810 --> 00:47:05.060 align:middle line:90%
I only met two of them though.

00:47:05.060 --> 00:47:07.740 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Are we concerned
that they're there?

00:47:07.740 --> 00:47:10.152 align:middle line:84%
Because obviously, we
can't get rid of them.

00:47:10.152 --> 00:47:11.610 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: I wouldn't
say concerned.

00:47:11.610 --> 00:47:14.280 align:middle line:84%
My understanding
is the main purpose

00:47:14.280 --> 00:47:17.490 align:middle line:84%
of continuing to engage in
military conflict is to test

00:47:17.490 --> 00:47:19.740 align:middle line:90%
weaponry and to test tools.

00:47:19.740 --> 00:47:23.430 align:middle line:84%
So we certainly see
that as a testing ground

00:47:23.430 --> 00:47:26.192 align:middle line:84%
for military
technology-- just get

00:47:26.192 --> 00:47:27.400 align:middle line:90%
better and better and better.

00:47:27.400 --> 00:47:30.540 align:middle line:84%
So in some ways, it's
just what we do there.

00:47:30.540 --> 00:47:32.730 align:middle line:84%
And it's a perfectly
good testing ground

00:47:32.730 --> 00:47:33.660 align:middle line:90%
for that material.

00:47:33.660 --> 00:47:36.910 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: At this point, have
you seen some of their craft

00:47:36.910 --> 00:47:38.910 align:middle line:90%
upfront and personal.

00:47:38.910 --> 00:47:41.370 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: Not the
indigenous species on Mars.

00:47:41.370 --> 00:47:43.980 align:middle line:84%
I've seen other
extraterrestrial craft but not

00:47:43.980 --> 00:47:46.470 align:middle line:84%
the indigenous species
who live on Mars.

00:47:46.470 --> 00:47:50.040 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And are we still
recruiting people to go there?

00:47:50.040 --> 00:47:52.080 align:middle line:84%
>>CRAMER: Absolutely
I mean, some people

00:47:52.080 --> 00:47:54.180 align:middle line:84%
are engineered from the
ground up like myself

00:47:54.180 --> 00:47:57.210 align:middle line:84%
and then parceled into a
program and then deployed.

00:47:57.210 --> 00:48:03.630 align:middle line:84%
Some people are recruited
from covert black programs

00:48:03.630 --> 00:48:05.370 align:middle line:90%
or other officer programs.

00:48:05.370 --> 00:48:07.830 align:middle line:84%
Some people are
requested or asked to

00:48:07.830 --> 00:48:10.800 align:middle line:84%
and some people are
just told you're getting

00:48:10.800 --> 00:48:12.810 align:middle line:90%
redeployed and get sent there.

00:48:12.810 --> 00:48:15.330 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Billy Carson has
been on the "Deep Space" Gaia

00:48:15.330 --> 00:48:18.759 align:middle line:84%
program and he talks
about recruitment.

00:48:18.759 --> 00:48:21.457 align:middle line:10%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:48:21.457 --> 00:48:23.040 align:middle line:10%
>>NARRATOR: Obviously,
being recruited

00:48:23.040 --> 00:48:25.590 align:middle line:10%
for missions such as
Randy Cramer was on

00:48:25.590 --> 00:48:29.300 align:middle line:10%
would have to be difficult
to say the least.

00:48:29.300 --> 00:48:31.090 align:middle line:10%
How could they get
anyone to volunteer

00:48:31.090 --> 00:48:33.262 align:middle line:10%
for such dangerous work?

00:48:33.262 --> 00:48:34.720 align:middle line:10%
>>BILLY CARSON: I
believe there are

00:48:34.720 --> 00:48:36.640 align:middle line:10%
